**Sec. 70001**
This section establishes that all references to the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 in this title apply to that Code unless expressly stated otherwise. It further specifies that the special rate change rules under Section 15 of the Internal Revenue Code do not apply to any tax rate changes enacted by this title. These provisions serve as the foundational definitions for interpreting the subsequent tax amendments.

**Sec. 70101**
This section permanently extends the individual income tax rate brackets established by the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, removing the original sunset date of December 31, 2025. It also modifies the inflation adjustment mechanism for the 12 percent and 22 percent brackets to use a specific base year for calculations. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70102**
This section permanently extends the increased standard deduction amounts and enhances them by raising the standard deduction for single filers to $23,625 and for heads of household to $15,750. It also adjusts the inflation indexing base years for these amounts to reflect 2024 and 2025 data. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70103**
This section terminates the general deduction for personal exemptions but creates a temporary $6,000 deduction for taxpayers and spouses aged 65 or older for taxable years before January 1, 2029. This senior deduction is subject to a phaseout for modified adjusted gross income exceeding $75,000 ($150,000 for joint returns). The provision requires a valid Social Security number for the qualified individual and applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70104**
This section permanently extends the Child Tax Credit and increases the credit amount from $2,000 to $2,200 per qualifying child. It mandates that the child must have a valid Social Security number issued by the Social Security Administration before the return due date to qualify. The refundable portion of the credit is set at $1,400 and will be subject to inflation adjustments starting in 2025. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70105**
This section increases the taxable income phase-in thresholds for the Qualified Business Income (QBI) deduction from $50,000 to $75,000 for single filers and from $100,000 to $150,000 for joint returns. It also establishes a minimum deduction of $400 for taxpayers with at least $1,000 of active qualified business income. These provisions apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70106**
This section permanently increases the estate and gift tax exemption amount from $5,000,000 to $15,000,000, indexed for inflation. It adjusts the inflation indexing base year to 2025 and removes the sunset provision that would have otherwise reduced the exemption. These changes apply to estates of decedents dying and gifts made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70107**
This section permanently extends the increased Alternative Minimum Tax (AMT) exemption amounts and modifies the phaseout thresholds to begin at higher income levels. It increases the AMT exemption phaseout rate from 25 percent to 50 percent for high-income taxpayers. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70108**
This section permanently extends the limitation on the deduction for qualified residence interest and clarifies that mortgage insurance premiums are treated as interest for this purpose. It removes the sunset date of December 31, 2025, making the current rules permanent. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70109**
This section permanently extends the limitation on casualty loss deductions and expands eligibility to include losses from disasters declared by a State Governor. It defines a State declared disaster to include natural catastrophes and fires, floods, or explosions warranting significant damage. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70110**
This section permanently extends the suspension of miscellaneous itemized deductions but creates a specific exception for educator expenses. It expands the definition of educator expenses to include coaches and nonathletic instructional equipment for health or physical education. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70111**
This section reinstates the Pease limitation on itemized deductions, reducing the total amount of itemized deductions by 2/37 of the amount by which taxable income exceeds the 37 percent tax bracket threshold. The limitation does not apply to the calculation of the Qualified Business Income deduction. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70112**
This section permanently extends the rules for qualified transportation fringe benefits but repeals the exclusion for bicycle commuting reimbursements and other specific fringe benefits. It also removes the coordination rule that previously disallowed deductions for certain expenses related to these benefits. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70113**
This section permanently extends the limitation on the deduction and exclusion for moving expenses, while simultaneously creating a new exception for members of the intelligence community. This exception allows intelligence community employees (excluding Armed Forces members) to deduct moving expenses if they relocate due to a change in assignment. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70114**
This section modifies the deduction for wagering losses by limiting the allowable deduction to 90 percent of the total losses incurred during the taxable year. The deduction remains limited to the extent of wagering gains for the year. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70115**
This section permanently extends the increased annual contribution limit for ABLE accounts and adjusts the inflation indexing base year to 1996. It ensures that the contribution limits remain indexed for inflation starting in 2026. These amendments apply to contributions made after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70116**
This section permanently extends the Saver's Credit to include contributions made to ABLE accounts and increases the maximum credit amount from $2,000 to $2,100. It also repeals a prior amendment from the SECURE 2.0 Act that had limited the credit's application. These changes apply to taxable years ending after December 31, 2025, with the credit increase applying to years beginning after December 31, 2026.

**Sec. 70117**
This section permanently extends the rule permitting rollovers from qualified tuition programs (529 plans) to ABLE accounts without tax consequences. It removes the sunset date of December 31, 2026, making the rollover provision permanent. These amendments apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70118**
This section makes permanent the tax exclusion for special pay received by members of the Armed Forces performing services in the Sinai Peninsula. It also expands the list of qualified hazardous duty areas to include Kenya, Mali, Burkina Faso, and Chad. These changes take effect on January 1, 2026.

**Sec. 70119**
This section permanently extends the exclusion from gross income for student loans discharged due to death or total and permanent disability. It expands the definition of covered loans to include private education loans and requires a valid Social Security number for the discharge to be excluded. These amendments apply to discharges occurring after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70120**
This section temporarily increases the limitation on the deduction for state and local taxes (SALT) from $10,000 to $40,000 for taxable years beginning in 2025 and 2026. The limitation is subject to a phaseout based on modified adjusted gross income exceeding $500,000 ($250,000 for separate filers) and reverts to $10,000 after 2029. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70201**
This section creates a new deduction for qualified tips received by employees in occupations that customarily receive tips, with a maximum deduction of $25,000. The deduction is subject to a phaseout for modified adjusted gross income exceeding $150,000 ($300,000 for joint returns) and is available to non-itemizers. It also expands the tip credit for employers to include beauty service businesses. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70202**
This section creates a new deduction for qualified overtime compensation paid to employees, with a maximum deduction of $12,500 ($25,000 for joint returns). The deduction is subject to a phaseout for modified adjusted gross income exceeding $150,000 ($300,000 for joint returns) and is available to non-itemizers. It requires employers to report qualified overtime compensation on Form W-2. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70203**
This section creates a temporary exception to the personal interest disallowance rule, allowing a deduction for interest on loans used to purchase applicable passenger vehicles for personal use. The deduction is limited to $10,000 of interest and is subject to a phaseout for modified adjusted gross income exceeding $100,000 ($200,000 for joint returns). The vehicle must be manufactured primarily for use on public streets and assembled in the United States. These changes apply to indebtedness incurred after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70204**
This section establishes "Trump Accounts," a new type of individual retirement account for individuals under age 18, with a contribution limit of $5,000 per year. It allows for employer contributions of up to $2,500 per employee and includes a pilot program providing a $1,000 credit for eligible children born between 2025 and 2028. The accounts must be invested in eligible funds tracking the S&P 500 or similar US equity indices. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025, with $410 million appropriated for the pilot program.

**Sec. 70301**
This section makes 100 percent bonus depreciation permanent for qualified business property, including certain plants and self-constructed property. It allows taxpayers to elect a reduced percentage (40 percent or 60 percent) for property placed in service in the first taxable year ending after January 19, 2025. These changes apply to property acquired after January 19, 2025.

**Sec. 70302**
This section allows businesses to immediately deduct domestic research and experimental expenditures rather than amortizing them over five or fifteen years. It creates a new section 174A for domestic research while maintaining the amortization requirement for foreign research. Small businesses may elect to apply this change retroactively to 2022. These changes apply to amounts paid or incurred in taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70303**
This section permanently extends the business interest expense limitation rules and expands the definition of floor plan financing to include certain trailers and campers. It removes the temporary expiration date for the limitation calculation method. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70304**
This section extends and enhances the paid family and medical leave credit, allowing employers to elect a credit based on wages paid or insurance premiums incurred. It clarifies that the credit applies even if leave is not taken and aggregates employers under common control. The credit applies to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70305**
This section creates exceptions to the 50 percent limitation on business meal deductions, specifically for meals provided on fishing vessels or at fish processing facilities in the northern United States. It allows for a full deduction for these specific types of business meals. These changes apply to amounts paid or incurred after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70306**
This section increases the dollar limitations for Section 179 expensing of depreciable business assets from $1,000,000 to $2,500,000 and the phase-out threshold from $2,500,000 to $4,000,000. It adjusts the inflation indexing base years to reflect 2024 data. These changes apply to property placed in service in taxable years beginning after December 31, 2024.

**Sec. 70307**
This section creates a new 100 percent special depreciation allowance for qualified production property, defined as nonresidential real property used in manufacturing or refining tangible personal property. The property must be placed in service between 2025 and 2031 and cannot be used for offices or administrative services. These changes apply to property placed in service after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70308**
This section increases the advanced manufacturing investment credit from 25 percent to 35 percent for qualified property placed in service after December 31, 2025. This enhancement aims to boost domestic manufacturing investment. The change applies to property placed in service after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70309**
This section amends the exempt facility bond rules to treat spaceports similarly to airports, allowing them to issue tax-exempt bonds. It defines a spaceport to include facilities for manufacturing, assembling, or repairing spacecraft and provides launch services. These changes apply to obligations issued after the date of enactment.

**Sec. 70311**
This section modifies the foreign tax credit limitation by allocating specific deductions, such as the Section 250 deduction, to foreign source net CFC tested income. It prevents the allocation of interest expense and research expenditures to this income category for limitation purposes. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70312**
This section increases the deemed paid foreign tax credit percentage from 80 percent to 90 percent for taxes attributable to tested income. It also disallows a foreign tax credit for 10 percent of foreign taxes paid on distributions of previously taxed net CFC tested income. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70313**
This section modifies sourcing rules for income from the sale of inventory produced in the United States and sold through foreign branches. It treats up to 50 percent of such income as foreign source for foreign tax credit limitation purposes. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70321**
This section reduces the deduction for foreign-derived deduction eligible income from 37.5 percent to 33.34 percent and the deduction for net CFC tested income from 50 percent to 40 percent. It also repeals the provision allowing a deduction for global intangible low-taxed income. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70322**
This section modifies the determination of deduction eligible income by including income from the sale of intangible property and other depreciable assets. It limits expense apportionment to expenses properly allocable to such gross income, excluding interest and research expenditures. These changes apply to sales occurring after June 16, 2025, and taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70323**
This section renames "global intangible low-taxed income" to "net CFC tested income" and repeals the tax-free deemed return on foreign investments. It updates various sections of the Code to reflect the new terminology and removes the exemption for a deemed return on foreign investments. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70331**
This section increases the base erosion minimum tax (BEAT) rate from 10 percent to 10.5 percent and adjusts the applicable thresholds. It also corrects the definition of a registered securities dealer. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70341**
This section coordinates the business interest limitation with interest capitalization provisions, ensuring the limitation applies regardless of whether interest is deducted or capitalized. It clarifies that capitalized interest is not treated as business interest for the limitation calculation. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70342**
This section expands the definition of adjusted taxable income for the business interest limitation to include amounts from foreign income inclusions under Sections 951, 951A, and 78. This change aims to prevent the erosion of the tax base through foreign income. These changes apply to taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70351**
This section permanently extends the look-thru rule for related controlled foreign corporations, allowing payments between related CFCs to be treated as foreign source income. It removes the sunset date of December 31, 2025. These changes apply to taxable years of foreign corporations beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70352**
This section repeals the election for a one-month deferral in determining the taxable year of specified foreign corporations. It requires these corporations to align their taxable year with the required year ending after November 30, 2025. These changes apply to taxable years of specified foreign corporations beginning after November 30, 2025.

**Sec. 70353**
This section restores the limitation on downward attribution of stock ownership, preventing U.S. persons from being treated as owning stock owned by non-U.S. persons. It creates a new category of "foreign controlled United States shareholder" subject to specific Subpart F rules. These changes apply to taxable years of foreign corporations beginning after December 31, 2025.

**Sec. 70354**
This section modifies the pro rata share rules for Subpart F income, requiring inclusion based on ownership on any day during the CFC year rather than just the last day. It also allows the Secretary to require taxpayers to close the taxable year of a CFC upon a disposition of stock. These changes apply to taxable years of foreign corporations beginning after December 31, 2025. [end of text]


